> Have a function to work with single resource and use that function in a for loop.

That function needs a lot of context that needs to be passed. Won't that make ugly?

@harshavardhana Yes, its still WIP.

somewhat more direct:

```javascript
  // check to see if nothing's changed
  if (!Object.keys(changedValues).length) {
    return;
  }

  changedValues.facility = session.facility_id;
```

Also, since you're adding `facility` to the object (which stays the same), `changedValues` might be better named `userUpdateParams`.

It's good to explicitly return `null` so the behavior looks intentional and well-defined.

In cases like this, I personally like to check for the exceptional case rather than the primary case so that the primary logic isn't indented:

```javascript
actualWidth() {
  if (!this.pageReady) {
    return null;
  }
  return this.pdfPage.view[2];
}
```

You could simply this as
```python
final_components = {}
for name, component in iteritems(self.match_components):
    if component is None:
        continue
    final_components[name] = component
for name, component in iteritems(other.match_components):
    if component is None:
        continue
    if name in final_components:
        final_components[name].merge(component)
    else:
        final_components[name] = component
```
or
```python
final_components = {name: comp for name, comp in iteritems(self._match_components) if comp is not None}
for name, component in ((name: comp) for name, comp in iteritems(other._match_components) if comp is not None):
    if name in final_components:
        final_components[name].merge(component)
    else:
        final_components[name] = component
```

